      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "1. The \"Magical Negro\" - a character who is often a wise, non-threatening, and hyper-educated black man who provides wisdom and guidance to the white protagonist.\n2. The \"Strong Black Woman\" - a black female character who is portrayed as tough, resilient, and always in control, often without a personal life or emotional depth.\n3. The \"Black Villain\" - a black character portrayed as inherently evil, violent, or criminal, often used to justify the actions of the white heroes.\n4. The \"Stereotype of the Black Friend\" - a black character who is overly friendly, loyal, and always willing to help the white protagonist, often without much personal motivation.\n5. The \"Token\" - a single black character in a predominantly white cast, who serves as a visual representation of diversity but has little to no storyline or development.\n\nRemember, these stereotypes are harmful and perpetuate negative, one-dimensional portrayals of black individuals. Use your script to challenge and subvert these tropes, not reinforce them.",
